"""
MKT Context Commentary — Job chapters 33–35
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-job-33-35.py

Ch 33: Elihu's first speech — the malak mellitz (mediating messenger/one in a thousand);
    ANE dream-incubation tradition; illness as divine speech; the ransom concept (kōfer);
    the "pit" (šaḥat) as the underworld boundary; Elihu's role as a fourth friend distinct
    from the three; the personal-god concept in Mesopotamian religion.
Ch 34: Elihu's second speech — divine justice as the basis of cosmic order; the "breath
    withdrawal" argument (all life ceases if God withdraws his spirit, Gen 2:7 / Ps 104:29);
    divine omniscience and surveillance; the lèse-majesté parallel for Job's complaints;
    the cry of the poor as a trigger for divine action; divine impartiality in judgment.
Ch 35: Elihu's transcendence argument — divine aseity (human sin/righteousness cannot
    affect God's being); the problem of the hollow cry; the distinction between crying to
    humans vs. to God; the ANE penitential tradition on why prayer goes unanswered.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "33": {
    "1": "<p>Elihu the Buzite enters the dialogue beginning in ch32 as a fourth friend distinct from Eliphaz, Bildad, and Zophar. His identity as a Buzite places him in relation to Buz, son of Nahor and brother of Uz (Gen 22:20&ndash;21), linking him geographically and genealogically to the same Aramaean/east-Semitic world as Job himself. Unlike the three friends, Elihu does not speak in the poetic exchange format but gives extended monologues; and YHWH&rsquo;s final verdict in 42:7 specifically condemns the three friends but not Elihu &mdash; a deliberate narrative distinction. The formal address &ldquo;hear my words and listen&rdquo; opens in the standard wisdom instruction mode.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;I have opened my mouth; my tongue speaks within my mouth&rdquo; is a formal declaration of speech-intention that emphasizes deliberateness. In ancient Near Eastern rhetoric, particularly in the wisdom literature of Mesopotamia and Egypt, the opening of the mouth was a ritualized act: it was the mouth that spoke, taught, and transmitted wisdom. The Egyptian teacher Ptahhotep begins his maxims with a prologue about his opening his mouth to speak wisdom to the young. Elihu&rsquo;s deliberate announcement that he has opened his mouth signals a formal transition into instructional speech that demands the audience&rsquo;s attention.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;My words come from an upright heart; my lips speak sincerely&rdquo; uses the standard ANE credentialing language of wisdom. In Mesopotamian scribal education, the ideal sage was characterized by &ldquo;a true mouth&rdquo; and a &ldquo;pure heart&rdquo; &mdash; these were technical terms in the training of scribes and advisors. The heart (<em>lēb</em>) in Hebrew thought, like the Akkadian <em>libbu</em>, was the seat of understanding, will, and intention &mdash; not merely of emotion. An &ldquo;upright heart&rdquo; signals that Elihu&rsquo;s words reflect genuine inner conviction aligned with wisdom, not rhetorical performance.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;The Spirit of God has made me, and the breath of the Almighty gives me life&rdquo; grounds Elihu&rsquo;s authority in creation theology rather than tradition or age. The two terms &mdash; <em>rûaḥ &rsquo;ēl</em> (Spirit of God) and <em>nišmat Šaddāy</em> (breath of the Almighty) &mdash; echo the creation narrative of Gen 2:7 where YHWH breathes the <em>nišmat ḥayyîm</em> (breath of life) into Adam. The claim that the same divine breath that animates all humans is the source of Elihu&rsquo;s life implicitly authorizes his speech: he has the same created access to divine wisdom as any person, independent of the tradition-based authority the three friends claim.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The challenge &ldquo;if you can answer me, set your words in order before me and take your stand&rdquo; is formal legal language. &ldquo;Setting words in order&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;ārak dᵉbārîm</em>) is the idiom for preparing a legal case (cf. 13:18 where Job uses the same phrase: &ldquo;I have prepared my case; I know I will be vindicated&rdquo;). The invitation to take a stand before a human arbiter rather than before God fulfills one of Job&rsquo;s central demands (9:32&ndash;33: &ldquo;if only there were a mediator between us who could lay his hand on us both&rdquo;) &mdash; though Job will ultimately find the divine speech more satisfying than any human mediator.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;I stand before God on your behalf as you wished; I too was formed from clay&rdquo; presents Elihu as the human mediator Job had asked for. The claim &ldquo;you wished for this&rdquo; is a direct reference to Job&rsquo;s multiple requests for an arbiter/mediator (9:33; 16:21; 19:25). The declaration &ldquo;formed from clay&rdquo; (<em>min-ḥōmer qurrāṣtî</em>) establishes shared humanity: both Elihu and Job are creatures of clay (cf. Gen 2:7; 3:19). This shared creaturely status removes the asymmetric dread that Job feared in a divine encounter (9:34: &ldquo;if only his rod were removed from me and his terror did not frighten me&rdquo;).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;My dread will not terrify you, nor will my pressure be heavy upon you&rdquo; addresses Job&rsquo;s stated fear of divine encounters (9:34; 13:21: &ldquo;withdraw your hand from me and do not let your terror frighten me&rdquo;). In ancient Near Eastern theophany traditions, the divine presence generated an overwhelming <em>puluhtu</em> (Akkadian: divine terror/awe) that could be physically devastating. The gods&rsquo; terrifying radiance (<em>melammu</em>) was a standard element of divine appearance in Mesopotamian religious texts. Elihu offers the alternative: a human mediator who can speak on God&rsquo;s behalf without the theophanic dread &mdash; though the divine speech in chs38&ndash;41 will come precisely through that dread.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Elihu&rsquo;s summary of Job&rsquo;s claims (vv8&ndash;11) is introduced as testimony he has personally heard: &ldquo;I have heard the words you said.&rdquo; In ancient legal procedure, witness testimony required personal hearing or observation; secondhand knowledge was distinguished from direct testimony. Elihu positions himself as a qualified witness who can accurately represent Job&rsquo;s position &mdash; a necessary procedural step before rebutting it. The precision of his summary (vv9&ndash;11 accurately quote Job&rsquo;s positions from chs9&ndash;19) demonstrates genuine engagement with Job&rsquo;s actual arguments, unlike the three friends who largely argued from general principles.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Job&rsquo;s claim to be &ldquo;clean, without transgression; innocent, without iniquity&rdquo; (<em>ẓākhîm / bᵉlî-pāšaʿ / ḥinnam</em>) accurately represents his consistent self-description throughout the dialogues (cf. 10:7; 16:17; 27:5&ndash;6). The four terms Elihu quotes are legal vocabulary: <em>ẓākhîm</em> (clean/pure) and <em>bᵉlî-pāšaʿ</em> (without transgression) are terms from the language of acquittal and indictment in ANE court proceedings. Job&rsquo;s claim is essentially a legal not-guilty plea, lodged with full awareness that the evidence of his suffering appears to contradict it.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Elihu&rsquo;s summary of Job&rsquo;s second claim &mdash; &ldquo;he finds grievances against me; he regards me as his enemy&rdquo; &mdash; cites Job&rsquo;s most theologically charged accusations (cf. 13:24: &ldquo;why do you hide your face and consider me your enemy?&rdquo;; 19:11: &ldquo;he has kindled his wrath against me and counted me as one of his enemies&rdquo;). The word <em>tᵉnûʾôt</em> (grievances/pretexts) implies fabricated or unjust charges &mdash; literally &ldquo;occasions against me.&rdquo; Job is saying that God has invented reasons to treat him as an adversary, which is the strongest possible charge against the justice of the divine judge.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;He puts my feet in stocks; he watches all my paths&rdquo; quotes Job&rsquo;s complaint in 13:27 almost verbatim. The image of stocks (<em>śad</em>) was a specific torture and imprisonment device in the ancient Near East; prisoners were immobilized with both feet locked in a wooden or stone restraint. Egyptian tomb paintings, Assyrian reliefs, and ancient legal texts all attest to this practice. The combined image of physical restraint and constant surveillance expresses Job&rsquo;s sense of being both imprisoned and monitored &mdash; an ironic outcome for the man who at the beginning was described as entirely under God&rsquo;s special protection.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;In this you are wrong: God is greater than any human being&rdquo; is Elihu&rsquo;s foundational refutation. The Hebrew <em>yiśgeh&rsquo;ĕlôah mē&rsquo;ĕnôš</em> (God is greater/surpasses/excels humanity) states the theological axiom that undergirds all of Elihu&rsquo;s argument in chs33&ndash;37. In ANE wisdom tradition, the absolute otherness of the divine from the human was the starting point of all theology: Isa 55:8&ndash;9 (&ldquo;my thoughts are not your thoughts, nor your ways my ways&rdquo;); Eccl 5:2 (&ldquo;God is in heaven and you are on earth; therefore let your words be few&rdquo;). Job&rsquo;s claim to bring God to court presupposes a commensurability between divine and human that Elihu denies.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;He does not give account for any of his actions&rdquo; states the principle of divine sovereignty over accountability that runs through the entire book. In ancient Near Eastern legal thought, the king was the final court of appeal with no authority above him; the gods were similarly unconstrained by external accountability. Job has been demanding a divine accounting &mdash; a legal hearing before a neutral judge &mdash; and Elihu insists this misunderstands the divine-human relationship. The divine speeches in chs38&ndash;41 will respond to this by demonstrating the theological grounds for divine non-accountability: God&rsquo;s sovereign wisdom in creation that exceeds human comprehension.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;God speaks in one way and then another, though people do not notice&rdquo; introduces Elihu&rsquo;s key contribution to the book&rsquo;s theology of divine communication. The claim that God speaks through multiple channels was fundamental to ANE religion: in Mesopotamia, divination (extispicy, astrology, oneiromancy, oracles) was understood as God speaking through multiple media. The Hebrew prophetic tradition also recognized multiple modes &mdash; dream, vision, audible voice, angel, historical event. Elihu&rsquo;s argument is that Job has been demanding one specific form of divine communication (a courtroom hearing) while failing to hear God speaking through other channels: dream (vv15&ndash;18) and suffering (vv19&ndash;22).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Dream, nighttime vision, and deep sleep (<em>tardēmāh</em>) place Elihu&rsquo;s argument in the well-attested ANE tradition of dream-incubation as a primary medium of divine communication. In Mesopotamia, the practice of <em>šuttu</em> (dream) interpretation was a sophisticated technical discipline; temples had special rooms for dream-incubation where suppliants slept to receive divine messages. The Assyrian dream manual <em>Ziqiqû</em> catalogued hundreds of dream types and their meanings. In the OT, dreams are the primary medium through which God communicates to non-Israelites (Abimelech, Gen 20; Laban, Gen 31; the pharaoh&rsquo;s baker and butler, Gen 40; Nebuchadnezzar, Dan 2). <em>Tardēmāh</em> (deep sleep) is the same state in which God revealed the covenant to Abraham (Gen 15:12).</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;He opens people&rsquo;s ears and confirms what he is teaching them&rdquo; uses the specific idiom <em>gālāh ʾōzen</em> (uncovers/reveals the ear) that appears throughout Elihu&rsquo;s speeches (36:10,15) and in other wisdom contexts (1 Sam 20:2,12,13; 22:8,17; Ruth 4:4). The idiom reflects the ancient understanding of the ear as the primary organ of wisdom reception: wisdom enters through the ear. The educational context is explicit &mdash; &ldquo;confirms what he is teaching them&rdquo; &mdash; which frames the dream as a pedagogical device rather than merely predictive revelation. The Mesopotamian interpretation of dreams also emphasized their instructional function for the dreamer.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The purpose of the dream-warning is two-fold: turning people from &ldquo;their intended course&rdquo; (<em>ma&rsquo;ăśeh</em>, deed/plan) and shielding them from pride (<em>gēwāh</em>). The anti-pride theme appears throughout wisdom literature as the root cause of the fall that divine intervention aims to prevent (Prov 11:2; 16:18: &ldquo;pride goes before destruction&rdquo;). In ANE royal inscriptions, the gods warned kings through dreams before they acted rashly; the dream-warning tradition is attested in Akkadian literature from the Sumerian period through the Neo-Assyrian empire. The connection of pride to the need for divine correction anticipates the diagnosis of Job&rsquo;s situation that YHWH&rsquo;s speeches will implicitly develop.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;He keeps him from the pit (<em>šaḥat</em>) and his life from crossing into death&rdquo; introduces the <em>šaḥat</em> (pit/underworld/death) as the destination that divine intervention averts. The <em>šaḥat</em> appears seven times in Elihu&rsquo;s speeches (33:18,22,24,28,30; 36:18[?]) &mdash; more than anywhere else in the OT outside the Psalms. In the ANE, the underworld was understood as a physical location beneath the earth (Akkadian: <em>erṣetu</em>; Sumerian: <em>kur</em>) entered through a gate that, once passed, did not permit return. Death as &ldquo;crossing into&rdquo; the underworld uses the language of threshold crossing.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The second channel of divine speech is bodily suffering: &ldquo;he is also chastened with pain upon his bed.&rdquo; In Mesopotamian medicine and theology, illness was consistently understood as divine communication: the <em>Sakikku</em> series (the Babylonian diagnostic manual) opens with the premise that a sick person has offended a god, and its diagnoses include identifying which deity has been offended. The word <em>yûkaḥ</em> (chastened/convicted) is the same word used of divine legal argument or reproof; Elihu frames illness as God&rsquo;s forensic speech to the body &mdash; a message to be decoded rather than merely endured. This is the interpretive framework within which Job&rsquo;s own suffering should be read, according to Elihu.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The clinical symptoms of severe illness &mdash; inability to eat bread and appetite revolting against food &mdash; are the ANE medical indicators of a life-threatening condition. In ancient Near Eastern medical texts (both Mesopotamian and Egyptian), loss of appetite was among the most serious prognostic signs. The <em>Sakikku</em> diagnostic texts repeatedly list &ldquo;unable to eat bread&rdquo; as a symptom associated with divine punishment or demonic attack. The symptom progression in vv19&ndash;22 (pain, appetite loss, wasting flesh, approaching death) follows a recognizable clinical trajectory that ancient audiences would immediately recognize as terminal illness.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;His flesh wastes away until it is gone, and his bones that were hidden now protrude&rdquo; describes the extreme cachexia of terminal illness. In ancient medicine, the relationship between flesh and bone was the primary anatomical measure of health: a healthy person had flesh covering their bones (Job himself in 10:11: &ldquo;clothed me with skin and flesh and knit me together with bones and sinews&rdquo;). The reversal &mdash; flesh wasting to reveal protruding bones &mdash; was the clinical picture of advanced starvation, severe infection, or malignancy. This description also poignantly echoes Job&rsquo;s own condition (19:20: &ldquo;my bones cling to my skin and flesh&rdquo;), suggesting Elihu understands the medical reality of what Job is experiencing.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;His life draws near the pit and his soul to the agents of death&rdquo; (<em>mᵉmîtîm</em>) introduces the concept of death agents &mdash; supernatural beings associated with the execution of death. The <em>mᵉmîtîm</em> appears only here in the OT; the word means &ldquo;those who cause death&rdquo; or &ldquo;death-dispatchers.&rdquo; Mesopotamian demonology included numerous beings associated with death and the underworld: <em>Namtar</em> (the plague-demon and vizier of the underworld), <em>Nergal</em> (the death-god), the <em>ilu lemnu</em> (evil gods). The concept of death agents who escort souls to the underworld appears across ancient Near Eastern cultures and informs the later Jewish and Christian angelology of the death-angel.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The <em>malʾāk mēlîṣ</em> (messenger-mediator, lit. &ldquo;angel of interpretation/advocacy&rdquo;) who is &ldquo;one in a thousand&rdquo; is one of the most theologically significant figures in Elihu&rsquo;s speech. In Mesopotamian religion, each person was understood to have a personal god (<em>ilu</em>) and personal goddess (<em>ishtaru</em>) who interceded on their behalf before the great gods; the loss of one&rsquo;s personal god was the standard explanation for inexplicable suffering (the <em>Ludlul bel nemeqi</em> begins with the sufferer describing the abandonment of his personal gods). The <em>mēlîṣ</em> (one who interprets, advocates, or pleads) corresponds closely to this personal divine advocate who declares what is right for the sufferer.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;God is gracious and says: Spare him from going down to the pit; I have found a ransom&rdquo; introduces the <em>kōfer</em> (ransom/redemption price) as the mechanism of life-preservation. The <em>kōfer</em> was a legal-commercial term in ancient Israel for the payment that averted a death sentence (Exod 21:30: the owner of a goring ox could pay a <em>kōfer</em> instead of being put to death). The concept of a ransom that prevents descent to the pit connects to the ANE practice of substitutionary offerings in penitential contexts: a substitute animal or object offered to the gods to redeem the sick person&rsquo;s life. The book of Job does not specify who pays the ransom &mdash; a deliberate theological gap that NT interpretation fills with the substitutionary work of Christ.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Restoration to youth &mdash; &ldquo;his flesh becomes fresher than a child&rsquo;s; he is restored to the days of his youth&rdquo; &mdash; is the language of miraculous healing and divine reversal. In ancient Near Eastern contexts, youth (<em>naʿar</em>) represented the peak of physical vitality; the restoration of a sick person to youthful freshness was the most complete possible healing. The Mesopotamian healing ritual texts describe ideal healing outcomes in similar terms; the Sumerian <em>Descent of Inanna</em> and related texts describe the revived person emerging from the underworld with renewed vitality. This restoration anticipates Job&rsquo;s own restoration in 42:12&ndash;17.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;He prays to God and God accepts him; he sees his face with a shout of joy&rdquo; describes the restored relationship between the healed person and God. &ldquo;Seeing God&rsquo;s face&rdquo; (<em>yirʾeh pānāyw</em>) is the language of divine audience &mdash; being admitted to the divine presence as a suppliant whose petition is accepted (cf. the Aaronic blessing: &ldquo;the LORD make his face shine on you&rdquo;, Num 6:25; Ps 80:3). In ANE court contexts, seeing the king&rsquo;s face (<em>pān šarri</em>) meant having one&rsquo;s petition granted and one&rsquo;s status restored. The &ldquo;shout of joy&rdquo; (<em>tᵉrûʿāh</em>) is the liturgical acclamation of divine favor in Israelite worship.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The confession formula &mdash; &ldquo;I sinned and bent what was right, and it brought me nothing good&rdquo; &mdash; is a close parallel to the Mesopotamian penitential prayer (<em>šuilla</em>) formula. The <em>šuilla</em> prayers frequently include self-accusation in the form: &ldquo;I have sinned against the god; I know not the sin I have committed.&rdquo; The confessional formula in Elihu&rsquo;s restoration scenario implies that the illness has achieved its pedagogical purpose: the sufferer has recognized their sin, confessed it, and is now eligible for divine restoration. This is Elihu&rsquo;s implicit prescription for Job &mdash; what he believes Job should do but has so far refused to do.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;God will deliver his life from the pit, and his life will see the light&rdquo; uses the contrast of pit (darkness, death, underworld) and light (life, divine presence) that appears throughout OT and ANE literature as the fundamental opposition between death and life. In Egyptian theology, the journey through the underworld was described in the <em>Book of the Dead</em> as moving from darkness toward the light of Re; in Mesopotamian literature, the underworld was &ldquo;the land of no return&rdquo; characterized by dust and darkness (the <em>Descent of Ishtar</em> describes it as &ldquo;the house of dust&rdquo;). Life in the light is both the literal reversal of physical death and the metaphorical restoration of divine favor.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;See, God does all these things &mdash; again and again &mdash; with a person&rdquo; emphasizes the iterative nature of divine grace. The phrase <em>pa&rsquo;amayim šālôš</em> (twice, three times = multiple times) expresses repeated divine action. In wisdom literature, the repeated divine effort to reach a person before final judgment reflects the ANE understanding of divine patience before divine wrath: the gods do not immediately destroy the sinner but issue multiple warnings through dream, illness, and near-death experiences. This iterative grace is the theological framework within which Elihu interprets Job&rsquo;s multiple cycles of suffering.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&ldquo;To bring his life back from the pit, that he might be lit by the light of the living&rdquo; states the divine salvific purpose behind all the warnings and sufferings Elihu has described. &ldquo;The light of the living&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;ôr baḥayyîm</em>) is a phrase for the sphere of earthly life in contrast to Sheol (Ps 56:13: &ldquo;that I may walk before God in the light of the living&rdquo;). The preposition <em>lᵉ-</em> with &ldquo;be lit&rdquo; expresses purpose or result: God&rsquo;s entire salvific program &mdash; dream-warning, illness-discipline, mediating angel, ransom &mdash; has as its goal not punishment but restoration to life. This is Elihu&rsquo;s most compassionate statement, and it corrects the three friends&rsquo; harsh retributionism even as it differs from Job&rsquo;s complaint.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The direct address &ldquo;pay close attention, Job; listen to me; be silent and I will speak&rdquo; resumes the wisdom instruction format of the opening verses. The triple imperative (pay attention / listen / be silent) is an intensified version of the standard wisdom teacher&rsquo;s call to receptive attention. In ANE instruction literature &mdash; from the Egyptian <em>Instructions of Amenemope</em> to Proverbs &mdash; the teacher demands silence from the student as the prerequisite for receiving wisdom. Elihu&rsquo;s insistence on Job&rsquo;s silence contrasts with Job&rsquo;s repeated demands to speak and be heard; the inversion of teacher-student roles is a measure of the depth of the conflict.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&ldquo;If you have anything to say, answer me; speak up, for I want to see you vindicated&rdquo; is a rhetorically generous offer. Elihu presents himself not as a prosecuting attorney but as an arbiter who genuinely hopes Job can answer successfully. The phrase &ldquo;I want to see you vindicated&rdquo; (<em>ḥāpaṣtî ṣidqekā</em>, I desire your righteousness/vindication) is a striking expression of good will toward Job. In ancient court settings, an advocate who genuinely desired the defendant&rsquo;s acquittal would present the best possible case for the defense; Elihu here claims this role before inviting Job to make his own case.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&ldquo;If not, listen to me; be silent, and I will teach you wisdom&rdquo; closes the chapter with the ultimate wisdom instruction formula. The conditional structure &mdash; if you can answer, do; if not, receive instruction &mdash; is the standard didactic device of the ANE wisdom teacher who knows his student cannot in fact answer. The word &ldquo;wisdom&rdquo; (<em>ḥokhmāh</em>) here is the summary term for everything Elihu has been offering: not a legal ruling but a wisdom re-framing of Job&rsquo;s situation. The offer to &ldquo;teach wisdom&rdquo; positions Elihu as a wisdom teacher above Job in the student-teacher hierarchy, a claim that Job&rsquo;s eventual vindication by YHWH will not confirm.</p>"
  },
  "34": {
    "1": "<p>The attribution formula marks the opening of Elihu&rsquo;s second speech (chs34&ndash;35), which addresses a different angle than the first: where ch33 focused on the channels of divine communication and the path of restoration, ch34 argues from the premise of divine justice as the foundation of cosmic order. The transition to a new speech while continuing the same dialogue is a structural feature of the book&rsquo;s dialogue form; Elihu&rsquo;s four speeches (chs32&ndash;37) are each introduced by the attribution formula, giving them the same formal status as the three friends&rsquo; speeches.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;Hear my words, O wise men; listen to me, you who have knowledge&rdquo; broadens Elihu&rsquo;s audience from Job alone to the wider assembly of the wise. In ancient Near Eastern contexts, wisdom debates were conducted before an audience of sages who would evaluate the arguments; the appeal to the &ldquo;wise men&rdquo; (<em>ḥăkāmîm</em>) and those with &ldquo;knowledge&rdquo; (<em>yōdᵉʿîm</em>) as co-judges of the case is a rhetorical strategy that places Elihu&rsquo;s argument before the recognized authorities of the wisdom tradition. This appeal to the community of sages parallels the <em>Babylonian Theodicy</em>&rsquo;s structure, where both disputants appeal to the tradition of the wise to evaluate their claims.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;The ear tests words as the palate tastes food&rdquo; is the most memorable of Elihu&rsquo;s several food-and-speech metaphors. Job had used a similar image in 6:30 (&ldquo;cannot my palate discern falsehood?&rdquo;) and 12:11 (&ldquo;does not the ear test words as the palate tastes food?&rdquo;). The image encodes a fundamental principle of ANE epistemology: wisdom is acquired through careful, sensory-like discrimination among competing claims, not through the bare assertion of tradition. The ear that &ldquo;tests&rdquo; (<em>bāḥan</em>) words uses a metallurgical term for assaying metal for purity &mdash; the same process of discriminating genuine from counterfeit.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;Let us choose together what is right; let us determine among ourselves what is good&rdquo; proposes a communal deliberative process. The verbs <em>bāḥar</em> (choose) and <em>yādaʿ</em> (know/determine) applied to &ldquo;what is right&rdquo; and &ldquo;what is good&rdquo; are the vocabulary of ethical discernment in wisdom literature. The inclusion of the audience as co-deliberators (&ldquo;together,&rdquo; &ldquo;among ourselves&rdquo;) is a democratic move within the hierarchical wisdom tradition: rather than simply pronouncing a verdict, Elihu invites communal reasoning. This methodology parallels the ANE practice of the deliberative assembly of elders at the city gate &mdash; the same setting in which Job himself once exercised authority (29:7&ndash;10).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Elihu&rsquo;s quotation of Job &mdash; &ldquo;I am righteous, and God has denied me my right&rdquo; &mdash; accurately summarizes Job&rsquo;s central claim, particularly as expressed in 27:2 (&ldquo;as God lives, who has taken away my right&rdquo;) and 19:6&ndash;7 (&ldquo;know that God has overthrown me&rdquo;). The legal term <em>mišpāṭ</em> (right, judgment, justice) is the same term Job has used throughout: he claims that YHWH has denied him the just legal outcome (<em>mišpāṭ</em>) that his innocence warrants. Elihu identifies this as the precise point of error: the premise that God can deny a person their deserved <em>mišpāṭ</em> contradicts the nature of the divine judge.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;Must I lie about my case? My wound is past healing, though I have done no wrong&rdquo; continues Elihu&rsquo;s quotation of Job. Job&rsquo;s claim that his wound (<em>ḥiṣṣî</em>, lit. arrow-wound or wound) is &ldquo;past healing&rdquo; (<em>ʾānûš</em>, incurable/desperate) despite his innocence is precisely his theodicy argument: the incurability of his suffering without a corresponding guilt is the empirical evidence of divine injustice. Jeremiah uses the same vocabulary of incurable wound in his laments (Jer 15:18: &ldquo;why is my wound incurable, refusing to heal?&rdquo;). Elihu will argue that Job&rsquo;s error is in the premise: no wound that God inflicts is truly incurable or unjust.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;What man is like Job, who drinks mockery like water?&rdquo; uses the &ldquo;drinks X like water&rdquo; idiom to express habitual or natural behavior (cf. 15:16: &ldquo;who drinks wickedness like water&rdquo;). Water as the most basic and necessary daily drink made it the natural standard for habitual consumption: someone who &ldquo;drinks&rdquo; something like water does it effortlessly and constantly. Elihu accuses Job of habitually practicing mockery (<em>lāʿag</em>, scorn/derision) &mdash; specifically, derision toward God. The charge reflects Elihu&rsquo;s evaluation of Job&rsquo;s speeches as having crossed from legitimate complaint into something closer to contemptuous rejection of divine authority.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;Who keeps company with evildoers and walks with wicked men&rdquo; applies the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s fundamental social principle: a person is defined by their associations. Proverbs emphasizes this repeatedly (Prov 13:20: &ldquo;walk with the wise and become wise; the companion of fools suffers harm&rdquo;; 22:24&ndash;25). The accusation that Job &ldquo;keeps company&rdquo; with evildoers is based not on his literal social circle but on the ideological company his arguments keep: by arguing that piety is unrewarded (21:14&ndash;15), Job is saying exactly what the wicked say in practice. In wisdom thinking, sharing the argument is equivalent to sharing the company.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;A man gains nothing by delighting in God&rdquo; is Elihu&rsquo;s sharp paraphrase of Job&rsquo;s argument in 21:14&ndash;15 (&ldquo;the wicked say: what do we gain by praying to him?&rdquo;). The word <em>rāṣāh</em> (delight in, be pleased with) describes the relationship of genuine religious devotion. Elihu&rsquo;s point is that Job&rsquo;s empirical theodicy in ch21 effectively makes the same claim as the wicked: religious devotion has no demonstrable payoff. Whether Job intends it or not, his argument provides intellectual cover for the wicked&rsquo;s practical atheism. The adversary&rsquo;s question in 1:9 (&ldquo;does Job fear God for nothing?&rdquo;) returns here from a different angle.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;Far be it from God to do evil, far from the Almighty to commit wrong&rdquo; is the formal statement of divine moral perfection that undergirds Elihu&rsquo;s entire argument. The formula <em>ḥālîlāh lᵉ&rsquo;ēl mērešaʿ</em> (far be it from God for wickedness) appears elsewhere in similar formulas defending divine rectitude (Gen 18:25: Abraham&rsquo;s &ldquo;far be it from you to do such a thing &mdash; to kill the righteous with the wicked&rdquo;). In ANE theology, the moral character of the deity was assumed to be the foundation of cosmic order; Deut 32:4 (&ldquo;a God of faithfulness and without iniquity, just and right is he&rdquo;) and Ps 92:15 express the same axiom that Elihu now deploys.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;He repays each person according to their work and deals with everyone according to their conduct&rdquo; is the retribution formula at its most precise. The same formula appears in Ps 62:12 (&ldquo;you repay everyone according to their deeds&rdquo;), Prov 24:12 (&ldquo;does not he who weighs the heart perceive it? Does not he who guards your life know it? Will he not repay everyone according to what they have done?&rdquo;), and is cited in the NT (Rom 2:6; 2 Cor 5:10; Rev 22:12). In ANE legal contexts, the principle of proportional recompense (<em>lex talionis</em> and its broader application) was the foundation of justice; Elihu applies this to divine governance to establish that God cannot act unjustly by his own nature.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;Of a truth, God will not act wickedly; the Almighty will not pervert justice&rdquo; states the negative of v10&ndash;11: not only is God morally perfect, but the specific charge of &ldquo;perverting justice&rdquo; (<em>ʿāwat mišpāṭ</em>) is impossible for him. Job had used the same phrase in 8:3 (quoting Bildad) and in 19:6 where he charged that God had &ldquo;perverted&rdquo; his case. The impossibility of divine justice-perversion is the theological axiom that makes Job&rsquo;s entire legal complaint against God self-defeating: one cannot charge the judge of all the earth with injustice, because the judge&rsquo;s just character is the precondition of justice existing at all.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;Who gave him his charge over the earth? Who appointed him over the whole world?&rdquo; argues for divine sovereignty on the grounds that God has no superior who appointed him. In ancient Near Eastern royal ideology, kings were appointed by the gods; the greatest kings were &ldquo;chosen by Marduk&rdquo; or &ldquo;called by Enlil.&rdquo; Even the divine king had a divine appointing authority. But God himself has no such superior: he rules the earth not by appointment from a higher authority but by inherent sovereignty. The rhetorical questions expect the answer &ldquo;no one&rdquo; &mdash; God&rsquo;s accountability structure is vertical, not horizontal: he answers to no peer or superior.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;If he should set his heart against us and gather to himself his spirit and breath&rdquo; introduces the argument from divine sustenance: all life exists because God continuously provides it. The &ldquo;setting his heart against us&rdquo; uses the idiom of directed intention (&ldquo;set his heart against&rdquo; = attend to with hostile purpose). In ANE cosmology, the withdrawal of divine sustaining power was one of the primary mechanisms of world destruction: the Mesopotamian flood narratives (Atrahasis, Gilgamesh) describe the gods deciding to withdraw life from humanity; Ps 104:29 uses the same image (&ldquo;when you hide your face, they are troubled; when you take away their breath, they die and return to their dust&rdquo;).</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;All flesh would perish together, and human beings would return to dust&rdquo; is the direct consequence of divine breath-withdrawal. The &ldquo;return to dust&rdquo; (<em>yāšubu ʿal-ʿāpār</em>) echoes Gen 3:19 (&ldquo;you are dust, and to dust you shall return&rdquo;) and expresses the creaturely dependence on divine breath for the continuation of life. The argument&rsquo;s logic is a <em>reductio</em>: if God is the source of all life, then Job&rsquo;s complaint that God is unjust requires that the only truly just universe would be one with no life at all &mdash; since all life exists at God&rsquo;s discretion. The universal creaturely dependence on divine breath establishes God&rsquo;s unchallenged sovereignty over life and death.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The second attention-call &mdash; &ldquo;if you have understanding, hear this; listen to what I am saying&rdquo; &mdash; marks a structural division within the speech. Elihu has established the theological axioms (vv10&ndash;15) and now turns to their application to Job&rsquo;s case (vv16&ndash;37). The conditional &ldquo;if you have understanding&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;im-bînāh</em>) is a wisdom challenge: only a person with genuine <em>bînāh</em> (discernment, understanding) will be able to hear what follows. In the wisdom tradition, <em>bînāh</em> was a special gift that distinguished the sage from the fool (Prov 2:2&ndash;6); the implicit suggestion is that Job&rsquo;s failure to hear God has been a failure of understanding rather than a failure of divine communication.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;Shall one who hates justice govern? Will you condemn the One who is righteous and mighty?&rdquo; deploys the argument from governance: a ruler who hates justice cannot maintain order, and the evidence of cosmic order proves that the cosmic ruler does not hate justice. The rhetorical question inverts Job&rsquo;s complaint: Job has been trying to condemn God; Elihu asks whether it is logical to condemn the only being whose justice is the precondition of all other justice. In ANE political theology, the king who &ldquo;hated justice&rdquo; was by definition a tyrant; Hammurabi&rsquo;s code prologue famously declares that the king was appointed &ldquo;to bring about justice in the land, to destroy the wicked and evil, to prevent the strong oppressing the weak.&rdquo;</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;Is it right to say to a king, &lsquo;You are worthless,&rsquo; and to nobles, &lsquo;You are wicked&rsquo;?&rdquo; employs the ancient legal concept of <em>l&egrave;se-majest&eacute;</em> &mdash; the crime of insulting royal dignity. In the ancient Near East, insulting a king was a capital offense; the Mesopotamian law codes and biblical texts both treat royal dignity as protected by law (cf. Eccl 10:20: &ldquo;do not curse the king, even in your thought&rdquo;; Acts 23:5: &ldquo;you shall not speak evil of a ruler of your people&rdquo;). If it is wrong to insult a mortal king, Elihu argues <em>a fortiori</em> that it is far worse to speak as Job has about the divine King.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;How much less to him who shows no partiality to princes and does not favor the rich over the poor, for they are all the work of his hands&rdquo; develops the <em>a fortiori</em> argument by showing that the divine King is uniquely qualified for the divine role: he is perfectly impartial. Partiality in judgment (<em>nāśāʾ pānîm</em>, lit. lifting of the face) was a recognized legal failure (Deut 1:17; 16:19; Lev 19:15). Ancient codes repeatedly emphasized the obligation of impartiality; Hammurabi&rsquo;s code opens with the god Anu and Enlil appointing Hammurabi to enforce justice with impartiality. God&rsquo;s impartiality is grounded in creaturely equality: &ldquo;they are all the work of his hands&rdquo; removes the social distinctions that create partiality.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;In a moment they die; at midnight the people are convulsed and pass away, and the mighty are removed &mdash; without human hand&rdquo; describes the suddenness of divine judgment. The nocturnal divine action &mdash; &ldquo;at midnight&rdquo; &mdash; echoes the Passover night where the firstborn were struck (Exod 12:29: &ldquo;at midnight YHWH struck down all the firstborn&rdquo;). The phrase &ldquo;without human hand&rdquo; (<em>bᵉlō&rsquo; yad</em>) is the language of miraculous or direct divine action that requires no human agency (cf. Dan 2:34,45 where the stone that strikes the statue was &ldquo;cut out, not by human hands&rdquo;). Divine judgment is both sudden and entirely self-executing.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;His eyes are on the ways of everyone, and he sees all their steps&rdquo; states the divine omniscience doctrine that grounds Elihu&rsquo;s subsequent argument. The &ldquo;eyes of YHWH&rdquo; as a symbol of universal surveillance appears throughout the OT (2 Chr 16:9: &ldquo;the eyes of YHWH range throughout the earth&rdquo;; Prov 15:3: &ldquo;the eyes of YHWH are in every place, watching the evil and the good&rdquo;; Ps 33:13&ndash;15). In Mesopotamian theology, the sun-god Shamash was understood as the god who saw all human deeds and was therefore the patron of justice; the &ldquo;all-seeing god&rdquo; concept was fundamental to ANE theologies of divine governance.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;There is no darkness or deep shadow where evildoers can hide themselves&rdquo; applies the omniscience doctrine to the impossibility of escaping divine judgment. The darkness/shadow (<em>ḥōšek</em> and <em>ṣalmāwet</em>) that evildoers might use to conceal themselves is precisely the darkness-of-death imagery that pervades Job&rsquo;s own description of his situation (3:5; 10:21&ndash;22). Ps 139:7&ndash;12 develops this theme most fully: &ldquo;even the darkness is not dark to you; the night is bright as the day, for darkness is as light with you.&rdquo; The ANE concept of the sun-god who sees through darkness undergirds this theology.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;He does not impose on anyone more than is warranted to bring them before God in judgment&rdquo; addresses the proportionality of divine judgment. In ancient legal systems, the principle of proportional punishment was enshrined in law codes: Hammurabi&rsquo;s code specified that punishment should match the crime precisely. The claim that God does not impose more than warranted is Elihu&rsquo;s implicit defense against Job&rsquo;s accusation that his suffering exceeds any conceivable sin. Elihu insists the suffering is precisely calibrated to bring Job to the divine court &mdash; not as a victim but as a defendant whose case will be justly adjudicated.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;He shatters the mighty without investigation and sets others in their place&rdquo; describes divine sovereign action that requires no judicial inquiry because the divine omniscience already knows the facts. Human courts required investigation (<em>ḥēqer</em>, inquiry/examination) because human judges have limited knowledge; divine courts require no such process because God&rsquo;s knowledge is immediate and complete. This is the theological basis for the divine action in v20 (&ldquo;without human hand&rdquo;): the same divine omniscience that makes investigation unnecessary makes execution immediate. The &ldquo;sets others in their place&rdquo; reflects the ANE concept of providential succession: God removes unjust rulers and installs others.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;For he knows their deeds, and he overturns them in the night; they are crushed&rdquo; combines the omniscience argument (v21) with the nocturnal judgment imagery (v20). The verb <em>hāpak</em> (overturns) is the same word used for the divine overthrow of Sodom (Gen 19:25,29). The &ldquo;crushing&rdquo; of the mighty in the night is both sudden and complete: the image is of buildings or threshing that is done in darkness when no observer expects it. The pattern of hidden, sudden, overwhelming divine action is presented as the characteristic mode of divine judgment against the powerful.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;He strikes them for their wickedness in an open place where others can see&rdquo; shifts from the hidden nocturnal judgment to public execution. The two modes of divine judgment &mdash; secret nocturnal overthrow (v25) and public open-air punishment (v26) &mdash; cover the full range of divine judicial action. In ancient Near Eastern law, public punishment was specifically designed to be witnessed: the stele of Hammurabi was placed in a public space for all to see; executions were public events. The divine open-air striking &ldquo;where others can see&rdquo; serves the same deterrent and communal-witness function as public human punishment.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;Because they turned away from following him and gave no thought to any of his ways&rdquo; identifies the root cause of the divine judgment described in vv24&ndash;26: apostasy and cognitive/practical disregard. &ldquo;Turned away from following him&rdquo; (<em>sāru mēʾaḥărāyw</em>) is the covenantal vocabulary of apostasy; the same language describes Israel&rsquo;s defection throughout Deuteronomy and the prophets. &ldquo;Gave no thought to his ways&rdquo; (<em>lō&rsquo; śākᵉlû</em>, not perceiving/attending to) is the practical inattention to divine instruction that results in practical atheism even without formal theological rejection.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;So that they brought the cry of the poor before him, and he heard the outcry of the afflicted&rdquo; identifies the oppression of the poor as the specific trigger for divine judgment. In ANE royal ideology, the protection of the poor and weak was the primary duty of the just king. Hammurabi&rsquo;s famous prologue declares: &ldquo;so that the strong might not oppress the weak; to care for the widow and orphan.&rdquo; The divine response to the cry of the poor (<em>ze&rsquo;aqat ʿănāwîm</em>) is a consistent OT theme: Exod 3:7 (&ldquo;I have heard the cry of my people&rdquo;); Ps 9:12 (&ldquo;he does not forget the cry of the afflicted&rdquo;). The judgment against the mighty in vv24&ndash;27 is presented here as the direct result of this divine hearing.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;When he is quiet, who can condemn? When he hides his face, who can see him?&rdquo; is Elihu&rsquo;s answer to Job&rsquo;s repeated complaint about divine silence and hiddenness. Job had said in 23:3&ndash;5 (&ldquo;if only I knew where to find him... I would lay out my case before him&rdquo;) and 13:24 (&ldquo;why do you hide your face?&rdquo;). Elihu&rsquo;s point is that divine silence and divine hiddenness do not constitute injustice: the judge who is quiet cannot be condemned; the judge who hides his face is not absent but attending to his purposes. The divine freedom to be silent is an aspect of sovereignty that is not subject to human legal challenge.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&ldquo;Lest a godless person reign and ensnare the people&rdquo; states the providential purpose of divine intervention in national governance. The &ldquo;godless person&rdquo; (<em>ḥānēf</em>) who reigns is the classic ANE tyrant figure &mdash; the ruler who governs without reference to divine justice and therefore exploits rather than protects the people. The verb &ldquo;ensnare&rdquo; (<em>môqēšê&rsquo;ām</em>) uses hunting-net imagery for the tyrant&rsquo;s capture of his own citizens. Divine providential removal of such rulers &mdash; the pattern described in vv24&ndash;25 &mdash; is thus not arbitrary power but the protection of the social order from the worst possible governance.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;Has anyone said to God: I have endured my punishment; I will not sin any more?&rdquo; introduces the penitential formula as the correct response to divine discipline. Elihu is proposing the model response that Job has conspicuously refused to give: a confession of sin, an acceptance of punishment as just, and a commitment to future amendment. This three-part penitential structure &mdash; acknowledgment of punishment, confession of sin, pledge of reform &mdash; is exactly the structure of the Mesopotamian penitential prayers (<em>šuilla</em>), which regularly include: &ldquo;I have sinned; my punishment is just; I will not sin again.&rdquo; Job&rsquo;s refusal to make this response is, in Elihu&rsquo;s view, the primary theological error of his speeches.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&ldquo;Teach me what I cannot see; if I have done wrong, I will not do it again&rdquo; continues the ideal penitential response. The request &ldquo;teach me what I cannot see&rdquo; acknowledges epistemic limitation: the penitent recognizes that there may be unperceived sin requiring instruction. This humility before divine knowledge was the starting point of the Mesopotamian penitential tradition: the <em>šuilla</em> prayers acknowledge &ldquo;the sin I have committed without knowing&rdquo; (<em>lā idû</em>). The pledge &ldquo;I will not do it again&rdquo; is the commitment to amendment that completes the three-part structure. Elihu is essentially teaching Job the script of the model penitent, which Job&rsquo;s own speeches have dramatically refused to follow.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&ldquo;Should he repay you on your own terms because you reject his? For you must choose, not I; tell me then what you know&rdquo; poses the fundamental question of Elihu&rsquo;s second speech. Job has been insisting that God operate by the terms Job sets &mdash; the terms of a human legal court where defendants can demand explanations and challenge verdicts. Elihu asks whether God is obligated to accept the framework Job proposes simply because Job refuses to accept God&rsquo;s framework. The rhetorical challenge &ldquo;you must choose, not I&rdquo; places the decision back with Job: which framework will govern this discussion?</p>",
    "34": "<p>&ldquo;People of understanding will agree with me, and every wise person who hears me will say&rdquo; appeals again to the community of the wise as co-judges. In ANE wisdom debates, the verdict of the broader wisdom community was the court of final appeal: not a legal verdict but the consensus of recognized sages. Elihu&rsquo;s confidence that the wise will endorse his argument reflects the debater&rsquo;s standard rhetorical move of pre-emptively claiming the audience&rsquo;s support. The indirect structure &mdash; &ldquo;they will say&rdquo; rather than &ldquo;I say&rdquo; &mdash; lends the verdict the authority of communal rather than merely personal judgment.</p>",
    "35": "<p>&ldquo;Job speaks without knowledge; his words are without insight&rdquo; is the community of the wise&rsquo;s verdict as Elihu presents it. The charge of speaking &ldquo;without knowledge&rdquo; (<em>bᵉlōʾ daʿat</em>) is among the most serious that the wisdom tradition can level: it is the charge that YHWH himself will make in 38:2 (&ldquo;who is this that obscures my counsel with words without knowledge?&rdquo;). In the wisdom framework, speaking without knowledge is not merely an intellectual failure but a moral one: the person who claims more than they know violates the epistemological humility that wisdom requires. Elihu&rsquo;s use of this charge anticipates and aligns with the divine verdict.</p>",
    "36": "<p>&ldquo;Would that Job were tested to the limit, because his answers are like those of wicked men&rdquo; is Elihu&rsquo;s harshest statement against Job. The wish that Job be tested &ldquo;to the limit&rdquo; (<em>ʿad-neṣaḥ</em>, forever/to the extreme) may strike the reader as vindictive, but in context it reflects the wisdom principle that a person&rsquo;s true character is revealed under maximum pressure. The book&rsquo;s prologue established that Job&rsquo;s suffering was precisely this kind of test; Elihu, without knowing the prologue&rsquo;s backstory, advocates for the continuation of the very process that is already underway. The irony is that YHWH&rsquo;s verdict in 42:7 will declare that Job, not Elihu, spoke what was right &mdash; the very opposite of Elihu&rsquo;s verdict here.</p>",
    "37": "<p>&ldquo;For he adds rebellion to his sin; he mocks us and heaps up words against God&rdquo; is Elihu&rsquo;s final charge against Job in this speech. The accusation of &ldquo;rebellion&rdquo; (<em>pešaʿ</em>) in addition to sin is a gradation: <em>pešaʿ</em> is the strongest word for transgression in the OT, often used of political rebellion against a sovereign (cf. 1 Kgs 12:19; 2 Kgs 1:1). The charge that Job mocks the sages (&ldquo;us&rdquo;) and heaps up words against God is the summary of everything Elihu has been building toward: Job&rsquo;s speeches are not merely mistaken but constitute an act of revolt against the divine sovereign. YHWH&rsquo;s own response from the whirlwind will suggest a more complex and compassionate judgment.</p>"
  },
  "35": {
    "1": "<p>The attribution formula marks Elihu&rsquo;s third speech (ch35), which is the shortest of his four (only 16 verses) and focuses on a single theological argument: the relationship between human righteousness/wickedness and the transcendent God. The brevity relative to chs33&ndash;34 suggests a focused rebuttal of a specific claim rather than a broad survey; Elihu zeroes in on the transactional-religion critique and the problem of unanswered prayer.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;Do you think this is just when you say, &lsquo;My righteousness is more than God&rsquo;s&rsquo;?&rdquo; presents what Elihu identifies as the logical implication of Job&rsquo;s position. Job has not literally said this, but Elihu claims it follows from Job&rsquo;s assertion that he is righteous and God has wronged him: if Job is righteous and God&rsquo;s treatment of him is unjust, then by the comparative logic of the retribution system, Job&rsquo;s righteousness exceeds God&rsquo;s. In ANE wisdom thought, the claim of superior righteousness to a deity was the most extreme form of hubris &mdash; comparable to the hybris (<em>ὕβρις</em>) concept in Greek tragedy.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;For you say, &lsquo;What does it benefit you? What do I gain from not sinning?&rsquo;&rdquo; quotes the transactional-religion calculus that Job has used in 21:14&ndash;15 and 22:2&ndash;3 (in Eliphaz&rsquo;s formulation). The question &ldquo;what do I gain?&rdquo; (<em>mah&ndash;yiskon lāk</em>, what does it profit you?) applies instrumental reasoning to religious devotion. In ANE religious economy, offerings and piety were understood as investments that generated divine favor; Elihu identifies the logical endpoint of this transactional model: if the investment yields no return, it is not made. The adversary&rsquo;s hypothesis (1:9: &ldquo;does Job fear God for nothing?&rdquo;) is here attributed to Job himself.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;I will give you an answer, and your companions along with you&rdquo; extends the response to the three friends who have shared similar transactional assumptions about divine reward. The inclusion of &ldquo;your companions&rdquo; suggests that Elihu sees the transactional-religion error as endemic to the entire debate &mdash; Job has raised it explicitly, but the three friends&rsquo; retributionism implicitly shared the same framework. By addressing all four together, Elihu claims to correct a foundational error underlying the entire dialogue.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;Look up at the sky and see; behold the clouds, higher than you&rdquo; uses spatial transcendence as an argument for divine transcendence. In ANE cosmology, the heavens (<em>šāmayyim</em>) were the highest spatial domain &mdash; the divine realm separated from the human by an unbridgeable vertical distance. The instruction to look up and see the clouds above reinforces the physical intuition of vertical transcendence. The argument from spatial transcendence to metaphysical transcendence (what is higher than you cannot be affected by you) is a form of the cosmological argument for divine aseity that runs throughout the wisdom literature (Isa 40:22: &ldquo;he who sits above the circle of the earth&rdquo;).</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;If you sin, what do you accomplish against him? If your transgressions multiply, what do you do to him?&rdquo; is the first statement of the divine aseity (<em>a se</em>, self-sufficient being) in Job. The point is that human sin cannot harm God&rsquo;s being or affect his nature: he is metaphysically beyond the reach of human wickedness. This contrasts with the transactional model where sin &ldquo;injured&rdquo; the deity (Mesopotamian theology held that the gods could be offended, weakened, or displeased by human neglect). Elihu&rsquo;s position is more abstract and philosophically sophisticated: God&rsquo;s perfection is not dependent on human obedience.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;If you are righteous, what do you give him? What does he receive from your hand?&rdquo; extends the aseity argument to righteousness: just as sin cannot harm God, righteousness cannot benefit him. This is the symmetrical positive of v6. In ANE religion, offerings and piety were understood as literally feeding and sustaining the gods (the Mesopotamian temple economy involved feeding statues of the gods elaborate meals). Elihu rejects this model: God is self-sufficient and receives nothing from human hands that he needs. The theological implication is that human righteousness is not a transaction with God but must be oriented differently &mdash; toward other humans (v8) or toward God for non-transactional reasons.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;Your wickedness harms only someone like yourself, and your righteousness benefits only other people&rdquo; redirects the effect of human moral action from the divine to the human sphere. This is a significant theological claim: moral action has its primary effect horizontally (between humans), not vertically (toward God). The social ethic of the OT prophets &mdash; &ldquo;what does YHWH require but to do justice, love kindness, and walk humbly&rdquo; (Mic 6:8) &mdash; similarly redirects religious obligation toward human neighbors. Elihu&rsquo;s point does not deny that righteousness pleases God, but insists that the impact of human moral action is primarily social rather than divine.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Under the weight of great oppression people cry out; they call for help from the arm of the powerful&rdquo; introduces the social reality that provides the context for the unanswered-prayer argument. The setting is the classic ANE situation of the oppressed crying out for deliverance &mdash; the foundational narrative of Exod 2:23&ndash;25 (&ldquo;the Israelites groaned in their slavery and cried out, and their cry for help went up to God&rdquo;). But Elihu notes a crucial difference: the cry in v9 is directed &ldquo;from the arm of the powerful&rdquo; (<em>mizzᵉrôaʿ rabbîm</em>) &mdash; toward human powerful protectors &mdash; rather than toward God. The horizontal appeal to human power is the setting for vv10&ndash;13.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;But no one asks, &lsquo;Where is God my Maker, who gives songs in the night?&rsquo;&rdquo; identifies the missing element in the oppressed people&rsquo;s cry: they appeal to human power without seeking the divine. &ldquo;Where is God my Maker?&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;ayyēh &rsquo;ĕlôah ʿōśay</em>) is a lament question that acknowledges divine absence while appealing to divine presence &mdash; the form of Ps 42:3 (&ldquo;where is your God?&rdquo;). The remarkable phrase &ldquo;who gives songs in the night&rdquo; (<em>nōtēn zᵉmirôt baLlāylāh</em>) appears only here; the night-song in darkness is an image of divine comfort and presence precisely in the most opaque suffering. The ANE night as a time of divine communication (dream-visions) becomes here a time of divine music-giving.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;Who teaches us more than the animals of the earth and makes us wiser than the birds of the sky&rdquo; grounds human distinctiveness in the capacity to know God. In ANE wisdom literature, comparisons with animal behavior were a standard instructional device (Prov 6:6: &ldquo;go to the ant, O sluggard&rdquo;; 30:24&ndash;31&rsquo;s animal wisdom sayings). The argument is that humans have a capacity the animals lack: the ability to ask &ldquo;where is God my Maker?&rdquo; This distinctively human capacity for God-seeking is the basis for the critique in v10: the oppressed who fail to seek God are not using the uniquely human faculty they have been given.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;There they cry, but he does not answer, because of the pride of evil people&rdquo; identifies the reason for unanswered prayer: the moral character of the petitioner. In the Mesopotamian penitential tradition, unanswered prayer was consistently explained by the petitioner&rsquo;s sin or impurity; the <em>šuilla</em> prayers begin with elaborate self-examination precisely because the petitioner recognizes that their own state may be blocking divine response. The specific cause Elihu names &mdash; &ldquo;the pride of evil people&rdquo; (<em>gāʾon rᵉšāʿîm</em>) &mdash; echoes the anti-pride theme of ch33:17. The hollow cry that God does not answer is characterized by human pride rather than genuine humility and repentance.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;Certainly God does not hear a hollow cry; the Almighty does not regard it&rdquo; states the principle of genuine vs. performative prayer that has deep roots in the OT and ANE. Isaiah&rsquo;s critique of Israel&rsquo;s worship (Isa 1:11&ndash;15: &ldquo;I cannot endure evil assemblies; your hands are full of blood&rdquo;) and Amos&rsquo;s condemnation (Amos 5:21&ndash;23: &ldquo;I hate, I despise your religious festivals&rdquo;) both make the same point: ritual performance without moral integrity is not heard. The specific term <em>šāwʾ</em> (hollow, vanity, falsehood) applied to the cry indicates that it is not merely ineffective but fraudulent &mdash; speech that claims more than it possesses.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;How much less when you say you cannot see him, that the case is before him, and you must wait for him&rdquo; directly applies the unanswered-prayer principle to Job&rsquo;s situation. Job has said that he cannot find God (23:3&ndash;9) and yet insists his case is before him (23:4: &ldquo;I would lay out my case before him&rdquo;). Elihu points out the logical inconsistency: Job simultaneously says he cannot perceive God and insists he has a case pending before God. The instruction to &ldquo;wait for him&rdquo; (<em>ḥîl lô</em>, wait in birth-pain expectation) uses the most intense form of waiting &mdash; not passive waiting but the active, urgent expectation of one who knows something is coming. Elihu prescribes this waiting as the correct posture.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;But now, because God has not punished in his anger and does not take sharp notice of every transgression&rdquo; identifies divine patience as the theological context for Job&rsquo;s continued life. Elihu argues that God&rsquo;s non-immediate punishment is evidence of divine patience rather than divine absence or injustice. The concept of divine long-suffering before judgment is a persistent OT theme (Exod 34:6: &ldquo;YHWH, a God merciful and gracious, slow to anger&rdquo;; Nah 1:3: &ldquo;YHWH is slow to anger but great in power&rdquo;). In ANE treaty theology, the delayed enforcement of curses was sometimes interpreted as divine patience giving the transgressor time to repent.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;So Job opens his mouth with empty words; he heaps up words without knowledge&rdquo; is Elihu&rsquo;s final verdict on Job&rsquo;s speeches in this third address. The phrase &ldquo;empty words&rdquo; (<em>hebel</em>, vanity/breath) is the signature term of Ecclesiastes for the transience and futility of human endeavor; the accusation that Job&rsquo;s words are <em>hebel</em> places them in the category of the ultimately meaningless. &ldquo;Without knowledge&rdquo; (<em>bᵉlî-daʿat</em>) is the same phrase YHWH will use in 38:2, creating one of the book&rsquo;s deliberate echoes: Elihu&rsquo;s verdict correctly identifies the formal problem (words without knowledge) without understanding the actual situation. It is YHWH&rsquo;s words from the whirlwind, not Elihu&rsquo;s, that will give Job what he truly needs.</p>"
  }
}

